This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the establishment of pasture land and the best way of protecting the forests of bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has sunk considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and works that affect breeding sites and the reduction of habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from head taxes.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, they have more use for the ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echo location to find insects and obstructions on the road when flying.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten competent experts who regularly carry out studies, monitoring of breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland’s first and only own bats reserve at Threeave Land Property in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bats.
