Update on algae flowering: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Commission on Fish and Animal Life (FWC) shows a general decrease in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spot-on blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, suggesting decreased concentrations.
A flowering of red algae extends around 210 km along the coast, from north in Pinellas to south in Lee County.
Spots are discovered around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations at or outside the coast of Pinellas County have been reported over the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Irritancy in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County is still reported.
No irritation was reported in the northwest airways of Florida in the last week.
